<section class="blk blk--cream2">
  <p class="eyebrow">The movement</p>
  <h2 class="sec">The honest state of a new movement.</h2>
  <p class="lead">Uncost is a nonprofit, nonpartisan movement working to lower the real cost of living using evidence, AI, robotics and open tools. It is also, right now, very new — so here is the honest state of it.</p>
</section>

<section class="blk">
  <p class="eyebrow">The four parts</p>
  <h2 class="sec">Four parts, one movement.</h2>
  <h3>01 — The Movement</h3>
  <p>Join in — pledge, take part, spread it. Reach people with visual, sourced explanations, bring them to a trusted front door, and offer clear paths to support, contribute, or partner. See <a href="/movement">The Movement</a>.</p>
  <h3>02 — The Case</h3>
  <p>The evidence — what living really costs. Define what one human needs, measure what it costs by region, explain the drivers, and publish open methodology.</p>
  <h3>03 — The Projects</h3>
  <p>Open tools that cut real costs. Translate evidence into open software, data tools, planning models, kits, studies, and playbooks that communities and qualified partners can use.</p>
  <h3>04 — The Assembly</h3>
  <p>Your voice — transparent and advisory. A structured, recorded supporter voice through proposals, surveys, and prioritization — within legal, fiduciary, and safeguarding limits.</p>
</section>

<section class="blk blk--ink">
  <p class="eyebrow">The mechanism</p>
  <h2 class="sec">How a cost gets uncosted.</h2>
  <h3>1 — Measure</h3>
  <p>Measure the current cost and its context, starting from public data.</p>
  <h3>2 — Publish</h3>
  <p>Publish the sources, dates, methods, and confidence labels — openly, so anyone can check the work.</p>
  <h3>3 — Break down</h3>
  <p>Break down the cost stack into its real components. {{ gapInline("about-mechanism-cost-stack") }}</p>
  <h3>4 — Match</h3>
  <p>Match plausible AI, robotics, sharing, infrastructure, or public-interest mechanisms to specific components.</p>
  <h3>5 — Package</h3>
  <p>Package the result as open evidence, software, a brief, or a playbook local groups can use. Uncost publishes; local operators decide and act.</p>
  <h3>6 — Track</h3>
  <p>Track whether total cost actually falls — and publish negative results with the same prominence as wins.</p>
</section>

<section class="blk">
  <p class="eyebrow">Working principles</p>
  <h2 class="sec">Three rules keep it honest.</h2>
  <h3>Receipts first</h3>
  <p>Every public number, claim, and cost estimate is sourced, dated, confidence-labeled, and open to correction.</p>
  <h3>Open and reusable</h3>
  <p>Models, methods, dashboards, and project designs are public and reusable wherever rights, safety, privacy, and partner terms allow.</p>
  <h3>Nonpartisan practical optimism</h3>
  <p>Bold but phased, lawful, measurable, and credible across political identities.</p>
</section>

